A single firm accounting for **52 Class I recalls** is the kind of number that makes even a raccoon stop rummaging and start highlighting.

## What mattered today

The latest Shelf Check pass over FDA enforcement data keeps circling back to the same problem: a handful of names are doing an absurd amount of the heavy lifting when it comes to serious food safety failure. CHETAK NEW YORK LLC remains the marquee offender, not because of one dramatic stumble, but because the volume itself becomes the story.

Made Fresh Salads Inc also keeps earning attention the hard way. Fresh, ready-to-eat products live in the danger zone where contamination problems become consumer problems fast. The more chilled distribution enters the picture, the less room there is for sloppiness.

Uncle Ray's LLC lands in the quieter class of recall embarrassment: labeling and ingredient disclosure trouble. Less cinematic than listeria, still deeply avoidable.

## Inspector Morsel's notebook

The FDA data reads like a diary of preventable chaos. Some firms trip once and vanish from the radar. Others seem to subscribe to the service.

What consumers should take from this is simple: repeated recalls matter more than polished branding. If a company keeps showing up, assume the visible recall is merely the part that failed loudly enough to make the paperwork.

## What to watch next

Expect the next week to keep rewarding the usual suspects. Fresh foods, allergen labeling, and broad distribution patterns remain the easiest ways to turn one plant mistake into a regional or national headache.

Inspector Morsel will be back when the shelf starts rattling again.
